  <h2 id="benefit">Benefits of Companion Planting:</h2>
  <p>Companion planting can boost soil nutrients, attract polinators, reduce pests, reduce weeds, reduce soil erosion as well as shelter plants. </p>
  <p>Some plants, such as legumes, can fix nutrients in the soil. Legumes (such as beans) fix nitrogen in the soil through a symbiotic relationship wiht the bacteria, Rhizobia.  Both the legumes and the bacteria, Rhizobia, are benefitting from their relationship. </p>
  <p>Plants that attract benefical polinators benefit your entire garden. They will help your plants increase their crop yeild.  Attracting polinators supports your local ecosystem. </p>
  <p>Certain plants will attract benefical insects that can reduce pests.  Aphids, a common garden pest, are eaten by ladybug larvae. By planting companion plants that attract beneficial insect, you can reduce the pesticides used in your garden. </p>
  <p>Other plants act as a cover crop to reduce soil erosion, weeds, and to improve soil health. </p>
  <p>Some plants can provide sun and wind shelter for other plants. </p>
