    </div>  
    
    <br>

    <li>Zucchini benefits from being planted with oregano and zinnias to attract polinators. Borage can also attrack polinators as well as deter pest worms. Dill attracts benefical insects that repel pests like cucumber beetles. It can also be planted with Buckwheat to reduce pests. Beans can fix the nitrogen levels in the soil which creates a more suitable PH level for Zucchini. </li>
    <br>
    <p>Pictured below is a Zucchini plant (left) and a Oregano plant (right)</p>
    <br>
    <div class="alignPics">
      <img src="images/companionPlants/zucCompanion.jpg" alt="Zucchini plant">
      <img src="images/companionPlants/oreganoCompanion.jpg" alt="Oregano Plant">
    </div>  
    
    <br>
    
    <li>Spinach benefits from being planted with herbs like cilantro, oregano, and rosemary to help repel pests. Beans can provide shade for spinach. Onion and garlic can repel pests with their strong scent. They also attract beneficial insects. Plants like broccoli and cabbage are good companion plants for spinach because their root systems are a different soil layer than spinach. When picking companion plants for your garden it is important to make sure they are not competing for nutrients. Planting lettuce with spinach can benefit both plants. Together, they produce more ground cover which lowers the soil temperature, allowing the plant to produce more.  Strawberries produce a similar ground cover effect when planted with lettuce.</li>

